summary.seg: Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 456 is a composite manuscript, with all of its parts probably deriving from manuscripts written in England in the late 14th century. A miscellany with a focus on the natural sciences, mathematics, and reading and research, the manuscript contains several widely-known medieval texts, including Iohannes de Sacro Bosco's Treatise on the Sphere, a popular text on computus known as the Compotus manualis, Alexander de Villa Dei's Algorismus, a previously unidentified copy of Simon Bredon's Theorica planetarum, an anoymous treatise on the planets, Richard de Bury's Philobiblon, and pseudo-Aristotle, Secreta secretorum. It also contains a short poem on music theory on p. 203 and a medical recipe for stomach problems on the same leaf.

It is not clear when all of the originally separate parts of this manuscript were brought together, but they must all have been together by the late 16th century, since the contents list on p. 2 written by Archbishop Parker or one of his circle refers to texts in each of the originally separate parts of the volume.

Dr Sarah Gilbert
Project Cataloguer for the Curious Cures Project
Cambridge University Library

A composite manuscript arranged as follows:

Quire 6-812 (pp. 127-198)
Quire 9two (pp. 199-202) |
Quires 10-178 (pp. 203-330)

note.p: Quire numbers 1-9, a-i written in pencil in the lower outer corner of the first recto of most quires, by a 19th-/early 20th-century hand. This quire designation sequences corresponds to the collation printed for the manuscript by M. R. James in his Catalogue.

binding.p: 18th century binding. Quarter bound in leather with parchment document sides over paste- or millboard. Five raised bands on spine; spine is unlabelled and undecorated. Several other Corpus Christi College Cambridge manuscripts are bound in this style and with these materials, e.g., Â Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 412, so it is likely that the College undertook a rebinding programme in the 18th century, perhaps focussing on the most fragile or poorly bound items in the manuscript collection. The portion of the document covering the front board is blank, but the portion of the document covering the rear board has legible text.
Paper pastedowns pasted over the turn ins. The right pastedown is blank. The left pastedown contains the number '456' (the present shelfmark) in pencil.

Two paper endleaves at each end of the volume, probably contemporary with the binding, ff. i - ii and iii - iv. Folio ii recto contains a 'Corpus Christi College, Cambridge' stamp in violet ink, and the shelfmark 'MS 456' written in black ink; all other paper endleaves are blank. Note that while most leaves in the volume have been paginated, the early modern paper endleaves have been foliated.

acquisition.p: Bequeathed to Corpus Christi College Cambridge in the will drawn up by Matthew Parker (b. 1504, d. 1575) Matthew Parker (b. 1504, d. 1575) in 1574; Parker died in 1575, and his bequest was transferred to Corpus Christi College over several years following his death. A pagination sequence in the characteristic orange-red crayon used by Parker and his circle is present on the rectos between pp. 1-7.

signatures.p: Two sets of leaf signatures visible in the lower outer corner of the rectos in the first half of each quire in this Part; one set of signatures in red ink, the other in dark brown ink. The red ink signature sequence uses the typical medieval forms of Hindu-Arabic numerals and has been partially trimmed away. The dark brown ink signature sequence uses the typical medieval forms of Hindu-Arabic numerals (but with a slightly more modern '4') and has mostly escaped trimming. See e.g., the lower outer corner of p. 9.
No quire signature particular to this Part.

Flourished initials in red and blue at the major and minor divisions of the text, typically a blue initial with red flourishing extending into the outer, upper, and lower margins. Paraph marks in red or blue throughout.

msItem.rubric: 127 UNiversis christi fidelibus ad quod tenor . presentis scripture pervenerit Ric. de Bury miseracione diuina dunelmensis episcopus salutem in domino semperiternam piamque ipsius presentare memoriam iugitur coram deo in vita pariter et post fata

note.p: Title 'Philobiblon' in the upper margin of p. 127 in a Parkerian hand in red crayon.

Ends imperfectly, missing the final few words of the text and the colophon. The missing text was added by a 16th century ?Parkerian hand as follows on p. 202 (full transcription):
ciei conspectum . Amen . Explicit philobiblon domini Ricardi Dunelmensis episcopi cognominate De Bury quondam episcopi Dunelmensis compilatus est autem tractatus initio in manerio nostro de Aukelande 24to die Januarii Anno Domini 1344, etatis nostrae .58. precise completo . pontificatus Vero nostri Anno undecimo finite ad laudem dei feliciter etc'

The Philobiblon was attributed to Richard de Bury Richard de Bury (1281-1345) for most of the medieval and early modern period. E. C. Thomas, who edited the Philobiblon believed the text to be wholly or mostly by Robert Holcot.

signatures.p:
Medieval quire signatures in ink and drypoint as follows:
Quire 3 has the signatures 'b1', 'b3'-'b4' in dark ink in the lower outer corner of the first, third and fourth leaves in the quire
Quire 4 has signatures 'b2-'b4' in dark ink in the lower outer corner of the second, third, and fourth leaves in the quire.
Quire 7 has partial leaf signatures beginning with an 'f' in drypoint in the lower outer corner of the rectos in the first half of the quire, now mostly trimmed away. The clearest example of this signature sequence is 'f vi' on p. 161.
